@node using "Using SearchGuide"

   Using SearchGuide
   ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

   SearchGuide is NOT supposed to be used from the Shell, but from inside 
   an AmigaGuide document.

   The template is as follow:
   
      SearchGuide VIEWER/K,PUBSCREEN/K,GUIDE/A,KW=KEYWORD/K,D=DEFAULT/K

   VIEWER is optional and is the viewer to be used to display the guide 
   resulting from the search. If not present SearchGuide will try 
   "SYS:Utilities/Multiview", if that fails it'll then try "Multiview",
   then "SYS:Utilities/AmigaGuide", and finally "AmigaGuide". (The last 
   two have been added in version 0.8.1.5).
   
   PUBSCREEN is also optional and is used for the feedback window and as 
   argument to the viewer for the resulting found guide, otherwise it 
   defaults to the default public screen (at least for the feedback window ;-)
   
   The GUIDE argument is mandatory and must be the name of the Amigaguide 
   document that is calling SearchGuide.
   
   KW=KEYWORD is optional, it allows searching directly for a keyword
   without going through the string requester. Has been added following
   a request from Pascal Chiozzi. This option is mutually exclusive with 
   the D=DEFAULT option.
   
   D=DEFAULT is also optional and exclusive with KW=KEYWORD. It just
   puts a default keyword in the string requester. Added following a
   request from Ours (Jérôme Chesnot) and another one from Gonzalez Rocha.
   This option is mutually exclusive with the KW=KEYWORD option.
   
   
   Some examples:
   ~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   You may add the following line to your Amigaguide document, called 
   "Your.guide", in our example:

   \@{" Search " SYSTEM "RUN <>NIL: SearchGuide Your.guide"}

   Where "Your.guide" is the name of the guide to which your are adding 
   this line!
   
   or:

 \@{" Search " SYSTEM "RUN <>NIL: SearchGuide VIEWER=NewGuideViewer Your.guide"}

   or:
   
 \@{" Search " SYSTEM "RUN <>NIL: SearchGuide VIEWER=NewGuideViewer Your.guide"}   

   or:

 \@{" Search " SYSTEM "RUN <>NIL: SearchGuide VIEWER=NewGuideViewer PUBSCREEN=MYSCRREEN.1 Your.guide"}
 
   or:

 \@{" Search " SYSTEM "RUN <>NIL: SearchGuide VIEWER=NewGuideViewer Your.guide KW=word_to_look_for"}

   or:

 \@{" Search " SYSTEM "RUN <>NIL: SearchGuide VIEWER=NewGuideViewer Your.guide DEFAULT=default_keyword"}
   
   And you should get something like this in Your.guide:
   
   @{" Search " SYSTEM "RUN <>NIL: SearchGuide SearchGuide.guide"}

   If you click on the above "Search" button. A reqtools string requester 
   should appear (if you didn't use the KEYWORD option!). 
   
   If you used the DEFAULT option, the keyword given as argument will
   already be in the string gadget, otherwise just enter the keyword 
   you are looking for, then press "Return".
   
   A small window will open telling you that SearchGuide is searching ;-) 
   
   Then a new guide will open (in a new window) with a list of all the nodes 
   containing your keyword, just click on the one you are interested in ;-)

   
@endnode

